replies.body:
> However, I want to also preserve champions like Mordekaiser and Xerath (who have different types of immobility).

Good take.  Mostly, I think that the various zone control patterns of these immobile mages have pretty much been done.  I think {{champion:268}} is a really interesting design, and a good example of how to grow League's mage pool in new and interesting directions.  Meanwhile, I think {{champion:161}} feels quite samey to other line skillshot mages, other than his parlor trick of offset Q shots.

> The trouble with introducing highly mobile champs to the mix is that the current mix of champions is simply unprepared for such a different idea. That's why so much controversy surrounds Rioters like CertainlyT--people don't like the fact that their favorite champs are becoming increasingly unsuited to  deal with the complexity and mobility that such new champs offer. 

I don't actually think that most of the old champions are struggling to keep up with mobile stuff.  Consider the following old and mostly immobile champions all happily coexisting with the new mobile champion designs:

Supports: {{champion:37}} {{champion:40}} {{champion:25}} 
Mages: {{champion:4}} {{champion:34}} {{champion:30}} 
Tanks: {{champion:27}} {{champion:54}} {{champion:36}} 
Fighters: {{champion:75}} {{champion:77}} {{champion:68}} 
Assassins (the class is mobile by design): {{champion:55}} {{champion:80}} {{champion:11}} 
Marksmen: {{champion:22}} {{champion:29}} {{champion:96}} 

Many old kits still work.  The difference here is that these old kits have lots of ways to play and can therefore react effectively when the other guy uses his mobility button.  When all you have is a gap closer, melee range cc, and a steroid, there's just not many ways to deal with the inevitable you gap close, they escape, you lose sequence.  You don't necessarily need a kit with mobility, but you do need a kit with more potential for counterplay and less reliance on having bigger stats.

tl;dr We need the fighter project.
